ildrens-books-site/childrens-books-site","webTitle":"Children's books","type":"blog","sectionId":"childrens-books-site","webUrl":"http://www.theguardian.com/childrens-books-site/childrens-books-site","apiUrl":"http://content.guardianapis.com/childrens-books-site/childrens-books-site","sectionName":"Children's books","references":[]},{"id":"books/booksforchildrenandteenagers","webTitle":"Children and teenagers","type":"keyword","sectionId":"books","webUrl":"http://www.theguardian.com/books/booksforchildrenandteenagers","apiUrl":"http://content.guardianapis.com/books/booksforchildrenandteenagers","sectionName":"Books","references":[]},{"id":"books/books","webTitle":"Books","type":"keyword","sectionId":"books","webUrl":"http://www.theguardian.com/books/books","apiUrl":"http://content.guardianapis.com/books/books","sectionName":"Books","references":[]},{"id":"culture/culture","webTitle":"Culture","type":"keyword","sectionId":"culture","webUrl":"http://www.theguardian.com/culture/culture","apiUrl":"http://content.guardianapis.com/culture/culture","sectionName":"Culture","references":[]},{"id":"books/teen-books","webTitle":"Teen books","type":"keyword","sectionId":"books","webUrl":"http://www.theguardian.com/books/teen-books","apiUrl":"http://content.guardianapis.com/books/teen-books","sectionName":"Books","references":[]},{"id":"childrens-books-site/series/childrens-books-top-10s","webTitle":"Children's books top 10s","type":"series","sectionId":"childrens-books-site","webUrl":"http://www.theguardian.com/childrens-books-site/series/childrens-books-top-10s","apiUrl":"http://content.guardianapis.com/childrens-books-site/series/childrens-books-top-10s","sectionName":"Children's books","references":[]},{"id":"type/article","webTitle":"Article","type":"type","webUrl":"http://www.theguardian.com/articles","apiUrl":"http://content.guardianapis.com/type/article","references":[]}],"references":[]},{"webPublicationDate":"2016-02-11T14:00:16Z","webTitle":"The Thing Itself by Adam Roberts review – a dazzling philosophical adventure","sectionId":"books","type":"article","rights":{"syndicatable":"false"},"id":"books/2016/feb/11/the-thing-itself-adam-roberts-review-novel","fields":{"commentable":"true","byline":"Julian Baggini","headline":"The Thing Itself by Adam Roberts review – a dazzling philosophical adventure","trailText":"A killer nerd’s dangerous pursuit of the ultimate truth offers a mystical reading of Kant","hasStoryPackage":"false","productionOffice":"UK","body":"<p>Physics sent people to the moon. The only place metaphysics has ever sent anyone is round the bend or off with the fairies. So you’d have to be somewhat eccentric to believe there might be any practical upshot of Immanuel Kant’s transcendental idealism, and more than a little unhinged to think those uses might include manipulating the fabric of reality to travel across time, teleport across space or rip out tendons by pure thought.</p> <p>That is presumably why novelist <a href=\"http://www.adamroberts.com/\">Adam Roberts</a> gave the idea to Roy Curtius, a character teetering on the edge of psychopathy, prepared to sacrifice the odd mere mortal’s life in his obsessive pursuit of ultimate truth. Lethal without having any ill-intent, he is perhaps the most dangerous nerd in fiction, a warning never to trust anyone who says his only friends are <a href=\"http://www.theguardian.com/world/philosophy\">philosophy</a> and the <a href=\"https://www.theguardian.com/science/grrlscientist/2012/apr/25/1\">Fermi Paradox</a>.</p> <p>Roy is the menacing nemesis of the main narrator of <em>The Thing Itself</em>, Charles Gardner, almost killing him in incidents decades and literally poles apart. But is Roy a lunatic or a genius? When Charles is courted by the mysterious Institute, which claims to have verified Roy’s central idea, it seems he might be both. Once Charles is roped in, his life becomes a bruising, perilous adventure in which it is never clear who is to be trusted, who is bonkers and what is real.</p> <p>If that were all there was to the book it would be a kind of infinitely superior <a href=\"http://www.theguardian.com/books/danbrown\">Dan Brown</a> romp, elevated by its genuinely intelligent philosophical core. Indeed, Roberts is not embarrassed to use the odd genre trope when needed, such as when he gets Charles to ask someone to run through Kant’s categories one more time, obviously so we can hear them.</p> <p>But this main narrative alternates with other chapters involving different characters and stories, each written in a completely different style, including <a href=\"http://www.theguardian.com/books/jamesjoyce\">Joyce</a>an stream of conscious, 17th-century vernacular, and a pastiche of Thomas de Quincey. We get some inkling of their connection to the main thread, but it is not until the end that we see how it all fits, and even then perhaps not completely.</p> <p>This is really walking the literary high wire, and Roberts not only keeps his balance, he makes the spectacle compelling. I can’t think of another such ostentatiously clever novel that is so dramatically successful, as rigorous psychologically as it is logically. Like Kant’s thing in itself, Roberts’s eponymous novel does not fit into any standard categories.</p> <p>Roberts is a fine writer who has the ability to make acute observations and find just the right words to describe them. You’ll know what’s being described by “That high violin whine, and the burn-y stench of chewed-up tooth, and the shards of discomfort than penetrate the protective sheath of anaesthesia” without me having to tell you. And you’ll certainly recognise the barmaid who displays “the sort of professional disinterest that makes British pubs such havens”.</p> <p>There are plenty of deft comic touches to lighten the philosophical weight, such as when the secretive, powerful Institute sets Charles up with a car and a stash of cash. But before it gets too <a href=\"http://www.theguardian.com/film/jamesbond\">Bond</a>, we are brought bathetically down to earth as he is instructed “you’ll need to keep receipts for purchases over five pounds”.</p> <p>This is too peculiar a brew to be to everyone’s taste. It’s often heavy going, which I mean as a compliment. When you’re dealing with the ineffable then you’re bound to wonder sometimes what the ‘effin hell is going on. Like a work of philosophy, <em>The Thing Itself</em> can’t be read too breezily because you have to attend very carefully to the ideas and arguments, and how they relate to each other. If you passively allow yourself to de dazzled by Roberts’s intelligence and invention, you won’t see what that brilliance is illuminating.</p> <p>Roberts offers a mystical reading of Kant that has some parallels with recurrent ideas in Indian philosophy. We live trapped in the world of appearances, unable to touch the thing in itself. But we perhaps can get some tantalising sense of the ultimate Oneness of reality, of which we and everything else is a part. Furthermore, this Ultimate is not inert and so therefore merits the kind of awe, if not worship, that we have given to gods. That’s why it doesn’t really matter that for all its ingenuity, “A/K” – Applied Kant – almost certainly won’t work. What Roberts shows us is that while metaphysics may leave the world as it is, it might change us.</p> <p>• Julian Baggini’s <a href=\"https://bookshop.theguardian.com/catalog/product/view/id/275776/s/freedom-regained/\"><em>Freedom Regained: The Possibility of Free Will</em></a> is published by Granta. To order <em>The Thing Itself</em> for £12.99 (RRP £16.99) go to <a href=\"https://bookshop.theguardian.com/catalog/product/view/id/346403/?utm_source=editoriallink&amp;utm_medium=merch&amp;utm_campaign=article\">bookshop.theguardian.com</a> or call 0330 333 6846. Free UK p&amp;p over £10, online orders only. Phone orders min p&amp;p of £1.99.</p>","liveBloggingNow":"false","shortUrl":"http://gu.com/p/4gg3k","wordcount":"832","thumbn