w.theguardian.com/tone/comment","apiUrl":"http://content.guardianapis.com/tone/comment","references":[]},{"id":"type/article","webTitle":"Article","type":"type","webUrl":"http://www.theguardian.com/articles","apiUrl":"http://content.guardianapis.com/type/article","references":[]},{"id":"tone/blog","webTitle":"Blogposts","type":"tone","webUrl":"http://www.theguardian.com/tone/blog","apiUrl":"http://content.guardianapis.com/tone/blog","references":[]}],"references":[]},{"webPublicationDate":"2016-02-11T07:29:11Z","webTitle":"Pretentiousness by Dan Fox review – why anti-intellectualism is the real snobbery","sectionId":"books","type":"article","rights":{"syndicatable":"true"},"id":"books/2016/feb/11/pretentiousness-why-it-matters-dan-fox-review","fields":{"commentable":"true","byline":"Steven Poole","headline":"Pretentiousness by Dan Fox review – why anti-intellectualism is the real snobbery","trailText":"Calling something pretentious is lazy, vacuous and smug – after all, it’s good at times for our ambition to outstrip our abilities. Those who invoke bluff ‘common sense’ are the actual snobs","hasStoryPackage":"false","productionOffice":"UK","body":"<p>The word “pretentious” is loaded with an impressive cargo of resentment, fear and self-admiration. If my enemy does not understand something, that’s because he is an idiot. If I do not understand something, that’s because it’s pretentious. Alternatively, I think I do understand something, but I want to stake my claim to having a superior right to work with such materials. This fellow, on the other hand, has got ideas above his station: he is pretentious. The use of “pretentious” as criticism is a smug, knowing wink to one’s presumed peers, and a mocking laugh at the unfortunate inferior.</p> <p>We hear constantly of pretentious films, pretentious TV dramas and pretentious modern art. In many cases these things will deserve to be criticised, but calling them “pretentious” is a lazy and vacuous way to do it. Writing and other arts are criticised as pretentious when they seem to aim at the highfalutin aesthetic or intellectual stratosphere while lacking the chops to see it through. But that, of course, is an inevitable risk of any ambitious creative work. To employ the word “pretentious” against it is empty as criticism, because all it means is “not good”; but it is disgustingly full as moral injunction: it means that it is better not to try at all than to try and fail. All art aspires to something it cannot achieve. All art is pretentious. And that is a good thing.</p> <aside class=\"element element-rich-link element--supporting\"> <p> <span>Related: </span><a href=\"http://www.theguardian.com/society/2016/feb/09/in-defence-of-pretentiousness\">In defence of pretentiousness | Dan Fox</a> </p> </aside>  <p>Some writers complain about the pretentious use of words, as though the very act of writing down words and hoping that others will read them and approve of one’s ideas is not itself fantastically pretentious in the first place. In his celebrated essay on computing, “In the Beginning Was the Command Line”, <a href=\"http://www.theguardian.com/technology/1999/oct/14/onlinesupplement14\">Neal Stephenson</a> says that it is pretentious to speak of “navigating” around a document. If such innocent metaphors are pretentious, whither fiction and poetry? Many such complainants are channelling George Orwell’s attack, in “Politics and the English Language”, on “pretentious diction”: here he inveighs against words we today find perfectly normal, such as extramarital, impermissible or predict. The example of Orwell shows that “pretentious” is the put-down of choice for a certain sort of bluff, meat-and-potatoes Englishman who distrusts foreign words and complicated ideas. But to present oneself as such is itself very often pretentious – as it was for Orwell.</p> <p>Even the more rarefied kind of intellectual may call his colleagues pretentious when seeking to curry favour with a certain readership and engineer a heroic self-image as an impatient straight-talker. The philosopher <a href=\"http://www.theguardian.com/commentisfree/2012/sep/10/karl-popper-enemy-uncertainty\">Karl Popper</a>, in his 1972 paper “Two Faces of Common Sense”, laments “the widespread anti-intellectual attitude which was so strong among the National Socialists, and which is again becoming strong among disappointed young people, especially students”. Such anti-intellectualism, he argues, is “if possible a little worse even than the pretentious and spurious, though sometimes quite brilliant, verbiage of philosophers and other intellectuals”. But the very use of the word “pretentious” here, as usual, signals anti-intellectualism. Popper, while pretending to be an enemy of anti-intellectualism among the young, feels free to indulge in it himself by calling other philosophers mere emitters of “pretentious verbiage”.</p> <p>The moronising accusation of pretentiousness, its blockheaded call to turn off our brains, if anything, is growing more common in our day, when everyone’s a critic on the internet. “On comment threads and online reviews lurk those for whom no creative project or act of criticism is ever quite good enough,” Dan Fox notes soberly. “Trolls are often the first to call out pretentiousness.” Against the trolls, beautifully, Fox here wields classical etymology, having noted that “pretentious” derives from the Latin for extending forwards. “The pseudonymous troll who trashes someone or something for being pretentious is, ironically, themselves being pretentious, holding in front of them a digital mask, a shield of clay.”</p>  <figure class=\"element element-image element--supporting\" data-media-id=\"dc2e3ab62cc8f914e53bcf9c1da601a59fc8dbbd\"> <img src=\"http://media.guim.co.uk/dc2e3ab62cc8f914e53bcf9c1da601a59fc8dbbd/0_0_2268_3372/673.jpg\" alt=\"Musician Howard Devoto\" width=\"673\" height=\"1000\" class=\"gu-image\" /> <figcaption> <span class=\"element-image__caption\">Musician Howard Devoto says ‘pretentiousness is interesting’.</span> <span class=\"element-image__credit\">Photograph: Jim Dyson/Getty Images</span> </figcaption> </figure>  <p>Fox’s brief and elegantly righteous essay on pretentiousness is definitely on the side of the angels, if arguably not quite pretentious enough. Its compacted historical sketches sometimes dissolve into mere lists namechecking a series of films or writers, while much of the book muses on the notion of authenticity, and explores the history of the theory of acting – in which everyone is indeed pretending. (Fox might have quoted Marlon Brando here: “Each of us in his own small way contributes to the aggregate pretension: national pretension. Nobody likes to admit it. He would much rather say: I am always right.”) But the author, who edits the art magazine Frieze, shines when focusing on the particular: he robustly defends individual artworks from the charge of pretentiousness, and there is a lovely sequence about the power of ideas in 1980s pop music. He quotes the musician Howard Devoto: “Pretentiousness is interesting. At least you’re making an effort. Your ambition has to outstrip your ability at some point.” Or, as Browning put it: “Ah, but a man’s reach should exceed his grasp, / Or what’s a heaven for?”<br /></p> <p>The most important contribution of Fox’s argument, perhaps, is his claim that what really deserves to be damned as pretentiousness is not an aiming-up but an aiming-down. “Anti-intellectualism,” he notes, “is a snobbery … The anti-intellectual is often anxious not to be marked as part of an educated elite.” And it is inverse snobbery in all its guises that might deserve to be called pretentious in a bad way. Fox approvingly cites Pulp’s “Common People” (1995), and comments: “Prolier-than-thou pretension is insidious”, because it “simply reaffirms class prejudice”. The lesson applies equally to Orwell slumming it intellectually as well as physically in London and Paris, and to our patrician politicians who adopt estuary accents. So we have got our idea of pretentiousness upside-down. To employ the word “pretentious” as a weapon against art that aspires to something difficult is to enforce social hierarchies of power. But when those in power pretend they have less than they do, that is truly pretentiousness without honour.</p> <p>• To order<strong> </strong><em>Pretentiousness</em><strong> </strong>for £10.39 (RRP £12.99) go to <a href=\"https://bookshop.theguardian.com/catalog/product/view/id/368201/?utm_source=editoriallink&amp;utm_medium=merch&amp;utm_campaign=article\">bookshop.theguardian.com</a> or call 0330 333 6846. Free UK p&amp;p over £10, online orders only. Phone orders min p&amp;p of £1.99.</p>","liveBloggingNow":"false","shortUrl":"http://gu.com/p/4ggqh","wordcount":"1036","thumbnail":"http://media.guim.co.uk/dc70a0382b07094e40c6696d2586a1537c7898ef/0_52_3674_2205/140.jpg","commentCloseDate":"2016-03-25T11:09:00Z","standfirst":"<p>Calling something pretentious is lazy, vacuous and smug – after all, it’s good at times for our ambition to outstrip our abilities. Those who invoke bluff ‘common sense’ are the actual snobs</p>"},"webUrl":"http://www.theguardian.com/books/2016/feb/11/pretentiousness-why-it-matters-dan-fox-review","apiUrl":"http://content.guardianapis.com/books/2016/feb/11/pretentiousness-why-it-matters-dan-fox-review","sectionName":"Books","elements":[{"id":"dc70a0382b07094e40c6696d2586a1537c7898ef","relation":"main","type":"image","assets":[{"type":"image","file":"http://media.guim.co.uk/dc70a0382b07094e40c6696d2586a1537c7898ef/0_52_3674_2205/2000.jpg","typeData":{"copyright":"Copyright MICK HUTSON / REDFERNS","picdarUrn":"PD*2845535","mediaApiUri":"https://api.media.gutools.co.uk/images/dc70a0382b07094e40c6696d2586a1537c7898ef","suppliersReference":"PULP","altText":"Jarvis Cocker of Pulp in 1995","caption":"Jarvis Cocker in 1995 … Fox approvingly cites Pulp’s ‘Common People’ in his argument against inverse snobbery.